06:06.166 --> 06:10.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As Republicans in Congress
struggle to reach agreement on
a plan to replace the Affordable

06:10.700 --> 06:15.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Care Act, we have heard from a
variety of interested parties
in recent weeks and months.

06:17.933 --> 06:21.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have included
hospitals, the pharmaceutical
industry, advocates for
the homeless and those

06:22.733 --> 06:25.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
with disabilities, as
well as lawmakers from
both political parties.

06:25.566 --> 06:30.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, we turn to the
March of Dimes and its
president, Stacey Stewart.

06:30.266 --> 06:35.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a nonprofit that focuses
on the health needs of mothers
and babies, especially with

06:37.033 --> 06:40.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
regard to preventing
premature birth, birth
defects and infant mortality.

06:42.100 --> 06:44.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Stacey Stewart, thank you
very much for being here.

06:44.166 --> 06:48.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what is your main concern
with the Senate version of
this health care reform plan?

06:48.666 --> 06:51.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STACEY STEWART, President,
March of Dimes: Well, the March
of Dimes, as you mentioned,

06:51.166 --> 06:54.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
what we care about is
the health of pregnant
women and their babies.

06:54.700 --> 06:59.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And our main concern with the
Senate bill, as it's proposed,
is that it would put at

06:59.033 --> 07:02.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
risk the health of many of
those women and their babies.

07:02.733 --> 07:07.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Medicaid today covers about half
of all pregnancies in the United
States and there are about 30

07:07.266 --> 07:09.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
million children that
are covered by Medicaid.

07:09.833 --> 07:13.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Under what the Senate
has proposed, about
6.5 million low-income
women of child-bearing

07:13.966 --> 07:17.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
age would lose their
coverage under Medicaid.

07:17.433 --> 07:22.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we think that that puts
at risk those women in terms
of them being able to access

07:22.166 --> 07:25.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
prenatal care and all the
things they need to do to have
a healthy baby, have a healthy

07:25.366 --> 07:27.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
pregnancy.

07:27.400 --> 07:31.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, about half
of pregnant women in this
country depend on government

07:31.133 --> 07:32.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
help in order to have
a healthy pregnancy?

07:32.833 --> 07:35.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STACEY STEWART: Right.

07:35.366 --> 07:37.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what Medicaid covers
is -- it generally covers
a lot of low-income
women who are pregnant

07:37.833 --> 07:42.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and making sure they have the
help they need in prenatal
care and also in delivering the

07:43.600 --> 07:45.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
baby.

07:45.633 --> 07:47.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But what it also covers, and
what a lot of people don't
understand, is that, if a baby

07:47.766 --> 07:51.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is born too soon, born
premature, if a baby
is born with low birth
weight or a baby has

07:51.966 --> 07:55.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
defects, Medicaid also covers
many of those babies as well.

07:55.366 --> 07:59.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So it ends up covering a lot
of the babies and providing
the support that many women

07:59.433 --> 08:02.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and families need to
make sure they can have
a healthy pregnancy and
have the support that

08:02.900 --> 08:04.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
babies need if there
are complications.

08:04.966 --> 08:08.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I think there
hasn't been a great deal of
talk about prevention, but you

08:08.933 --> 08:12.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
were telling us that
prevention is a very -
- is a big part of this.

08:12.400 --> 08:15.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STACEY STEWART: Well, I think
one of the big conversations
that is going on right now is,

08:15.733 --> 08:17.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
how do we stabilize
the health market?

08:17.833 --> 08:22.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think -- how do
we stabilize Medicaid
and I think stabilize
health care in general?

08:22.033 --> 08:26.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think one of the
conversations we really
need to have as a country
is, how do we begin

08:26.033 --> 08:31.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do even more, to put more
of the emphasis on prevention
and care earlier on, vs. having

08:32.633 --> 08:34.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
a system that really is
funding a lot of chronic
disease and illness?

08:34.666 --> 08:39.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, one of the reasons we focus
so much on maternity coverage
and prenatal care is because

08:39.366 --> 08:43.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
that's what happens to
enable those women to
have healthy babies.

08:43.233 --> 08:47.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If they get the help they
need, and certainly even before
they get pregnant, if they are

08:47.066 --> 08:51.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
healthy before they even get
pregnant, that is going to be
what creates the best outcome

08:51.733 --> 08:52.966 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for that baby.

08:52.966 --> 08:55.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so healthy women
equals healthy babies.

08:55.900 --> 09:00.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The more and more we
can put more emphasis
on early prevention
efforts and fund a system

09:00.600 --> 09:05.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that actually focuses on that,
we think will improve health
outcomes, reduce cost, reduce

09:06.766 --> 09:08.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
premiums, which is what
I think everybody wants.

09:08.866 --> 09:12.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Isn't it
the case, though, Stacey
Stewart, that, under
traditional Medicaid,

09:14.633 --> 09:18.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
states are required to cover
pregnancy, to cover prenatal
care, to cover babies?

09:20.633 --> 09:25.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, even if Medicaid is scaled
back, which looks like would
be the case under the Senate

09:27.133 --> 09:30.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plan, the Republican plan, they
would still be required to cover
women in these circumstances,

09:30.933 --> 09:33.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wouldn't they?

09:33.000 --> 09:35.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
STACEY STEWART: Well,
the problem is, is
that with reductions as
they're proposed, we're

09:35.833 --> 09:39.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not exactly sure if -- how much
of the need would be covered.

09:39.500 --> 09:41.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's always a question.

09:41.533 --> 09:45.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And with women coming off of
Medicaid coverage as a result
of the pullback of the expansion

09:45.966 --> 09:49.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Medicaid, I think there is
a real concern that we have.

09:49.066 --> 09:51.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And, of course, the
concern isn't just in
the Medicaid market.

09:51.333 --> 09:53.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The concern is also
in the private market.

09:53.400 --> 09:58.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, what a lot of people
don't realize is, before
the Affordable Care
Act, private health

10:00.266 --> 10:03.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
care plans didn't necessarily
include maternity coverage
as a requirement, as
did employer-based

10:04.000 --> 10:06.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
plans or Medicaid.

10:06.000 --> 10:08.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so we have got to look
at the totality of the health
care system in making sure that

10:08.700 --> 10:13.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all women, irrespective of
them being in a private plan or
Medicaid, have access to those

10:13.133 --> 10:15.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
resources they need.

10:15.166 --> 10:18.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we believe that much
of the support that women
need could be at risk.

10:18.333 --> 10:20.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that's what our
primary concern is.

10:20.366 --> 10:24.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you answer
the argument from conservatives
that, look, something has

10:24.533 --> 10:29.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
got to be done, that Medicaid
has grown at a rate that's
just out of control, cannot

10:29.133 --> 10:34.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be sustained, and unless some
methods are found to scale
that back, Medicaid is not

10:35.600 --> 10:37.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to be there in the long
term for people who need it?

10:37.633 --> 10:39.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
STACEY STEWART: Well,
we share that concern.

10:39.666 --> 10:44.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Obviously, the costs of
Medicaid are exorbitant
and they're growing.

10:44.266 --> 10:49.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But let's look at what's really
going on in the Medicaid market.

10:50.700 --> 10:53.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have got a lot of low-income
women, many women of color.

10:53.500 --> 10:55.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And what we see are health
outcomes not improving.

10:55.600 --> 10:59.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the big concerns that
we have at the March of Dimes
